<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="template-spec">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Template for spec.md: WHAT and WHY? Includes Problem Statement, Personas, User Stories, FR (MoSCoW), NFR (numeric targets), AC (Given-When-Then), Out of Scope, Assumptions, Dependencies.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>spec</tag>
      <tag>template</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>acceptance-criteria</tag>
      <tag>moscow</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>spec</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Template: Specification</title>
    <summary>A fill-in-the-blanks template for spec.md — the document that answers "WHAT are we building and WHY?" Sections: Reference Documents, Overview, Problem Statement (Who/Problem/Impact/Solution/Metric), User Personas, User Stories (As a/I want/So that), Functional Requirements table (FR-X with MoSCoW), Non-Functional Requirements table (NFR-X with targets), Acceptance Criteria (Given-When-Then), Out of Scope table, Assumptions and Constraints, and Dependencies.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Without a standard template, specs written by different agents or humans diverge in structure, omit sections (especially Out of Scope and NFRs), and produce untraceable requirements. A shared template ensures every FR has a US reference, every AC has a Given-When-Then form, and every spec explicitly states what is NOT being built — preventing scope creep when design begins.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting any new feature that will be executed by a subagent — the template enforces the FR/AC structure the executor needs</item>
        <item>When a stakeholder provides fuzzy requirements and you need a structured artifact to validate understanding</item>
        <item>Before writing design.md — spec must exist and be approved first</item>
        <item>Generating spec drafts from user interviews, chat logs, or product briefs</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Hot-fixes and patches — spec overhead exceeds value for changes under ~2 hours of work</item>
        <item>Pure infrastructure tasks with no user-facing behavior</item>
        <item>Research spikes where requirements are deliberately undefined</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="required-sections">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every spec.md must contain all required sections: Reference Documents, Overview, Problem Statement, User Personas (minimum 2), User Stories, Functional Requirements table (FR-X), Non-Functional Requirements table (NFR-X), Acceptance Criteria, Out of Scope, Assumptions and Constraints, and Dependencies.</statement>
        <rationale>Missing sections cause design agents to make ungrounded decisions. Out of Scope is the most commonly omitted section and the most important for preventing scope creep.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Reference Documents — links to constitution.md and related done/ specs</item>
        <item>Overview — 2-3 sentences describing the feature and its purpose</item>
        <item>Problem Statement — Who, Problem, Impact, Solution (high-level only), Success Metric</item>
        <item>User Personas — minimum 2, each with Role, Goal, Pain Points, Context</item>
        <item>User Stories — "As a / I want / So that" with US-X IDs and MoSCoW priority</item>
        <item>Functional Requirements — FR-X table with Requirement, Traces To (US-X), Priority (MoSCoW)</item>
        <item>Non-Functional Requirements — NFR-X table with Category, Requirement, Target (numeric), Priority</item>
        <item>Acceptance Criteria — AC-X in Given-When-Then format, linked to FR-X</item>
        <item>Out of Scope — explicit table of named excluded features with reason and timeline</item>
        <item>Assumptions and Constraints — technical and business constraints</item>
        <item>Dependencies — internal (other features) and external (APIs, services)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="spec-vs-design">
      <rule>
        <statement>Spec contains WHAT and WHY only. Any sentence describing HOW something works belongs in design.md, not spec.md.</statement>
        <rationale>Implementation details in spec.md become stale when design decisions change, causing version drift between spec and design.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad" title="Implementation detail leaking into spec">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[FR-003: System SHALL use bcrypt with cost factor 12 for password hashing.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Correct spec requirement — what, not how">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[FR-003: System SHALL store passwords using a cryptographically secure one-way hash that is resistant to brute-force attacks. [Must]]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="moscow-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Assign MoSCoW priority (Must/Should/Could/Won't) to every FR and NFR. Unclassified requirements default to "Must" during implementation, causing scope creep.</statement>
        <rationale>Without explicit priority, executor agents treat all requirements as equally urgent and implement Could requirements before Should requirements.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="nfr-numeric-targets">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every non-functional requirement must include a specific numeric target and measurement unit. "Fast" and "responsive" are not valid NFR values.</statement>
        <rationale>NFRs without numbers are unenforceable in testing and cannot be validated by automated checks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad" title="Vague NFR">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[NFR-001: System should have fast response times.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Measurable NFR">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[NFR-001: API response time SHALL be &lt; 500ms at p95 under 100 concurrent users. [Must]]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="status-gate">
      <rule>
        <statement>Spec must reach Approved status before design begins. Never hand a Draft or Review spec to an executor agent.</statement>
        <rationale>Design decisions made against unapproved requirements cause rework when requirements change during the review cycle.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Out of Scope section lists only generic exclusions ("mobile app", "internationalization").</description>
        <reason>Out of Scope must name specific features that were discussed in requirements gathering and explicitly rejected with reasons. Generic exclusions do not prevent scope creep.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>User stories without "so that" benefit clause.</description>
        <reason>The benefit clause is where business value lives. Stories without it cannot be prioritized against each other.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Single persona for a multi-user feature.</description>
        <reason>Different personas have different goals and pain points. A single persona produces requirements that serve one audience and silently exclude others.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="checklist">
      <p>Ordered checklist for filling each section of spec.md from file creation through quality gate review, covering all 12 phases.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Phase 1: Prepare File — create at .aidocs/features/{status}/{feature}/spec.md, fill metadata, add Reference Documents</item>
        <item>Phase 2: Overview — write 2-3 sentences explaining feature purpose and what users can do</item>
        <item>Phase 3: Problem Statement — define WHO, state PROBLEM, explain IMPACT, outline SOLUTION, define SUCCESS METRIC</item>
        <item>Phase 4: User Personas — create minimum 2 distinct personas; for each: Role, Goal, Pain Points, Context</item>
        <item>Phase 5: User Stories — create US-001, US-002, etc.; format: "As a [persona], I want [action], so that [benefit]"; assign MoSCoW priority</item>
        <item>Phase 6: Functional Requirements — create FR-001, FR-002, etc. table with ID, Requirement, Traces To, Priority; write as "System SHALL [specific action]"</item>
        <item>Phase 7: Non-Functional Requirements — create NFR-001, NFR-002, etc.; cover Performance, Security, Scalability, Availability; every NFR must have numeric target</item>
        <item>Phase 8: Acceptance Criteria — create AC-001, AC-002, etc.; use Given-When-Then format; cover happy path, error cases, boundary conditions</item>
        <item>Phase 9: Out of Scope — list specific features discussed and explicitly rejected; for each: reason (Phase 2, Never, To be decided) and timeline; minimum 3 items</item>
        <item>Phase 10: Assumptions and Constraints — list assumptions about user behavior, system state; list technical and business constraints</item>
        <item>Phase 11: Dependencies — identify internal dependencies (other features needed first); identify external dependencies (APIs, services)</item>
        <item>Phase 12: Quality Gate — problem statement is SMART and clear; personas defined with Role/Goal/Pain Points/Context; user stories have "so that" benefit; all FRs trace to US-X; all NFRs have numeric targets; all ACs use Given-When-Then with specific values; Out of Scope names specific features (not generic); no implementation details; status advanced to Review</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Write the Problem Statement before anything else — if you cannot fill "Who / Problem / Impact / Solution / Metric", the feature is not ready to spec</item>
        <item>Keep FR text short and unambiguous: "System SHALL allow X" — one verb, one object</item>
        <item>Explicitly list at least three Out of Scope items; this prevents scope creep during design phase</item>
        <item>Status field (Draft → Review → Approved) is a human gate — never hand a Draft spec to an executor agent</item>
        <item>Condense the template for MVP features: Problem Statement + User Stories + FRs + ACs + Out of Scope is sufficient</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents tend to merge design decisions into specs — any sentence describing HOW something works belongs in design.md, not spec.md; enforce this with a review prompt</item>
        <item>"Acceptance Criteria" sections generated by agents often contain non-testable criteria ("user experience is smooth") — run a dedicated AC-quality check pass</item>
        <item>Template version drift: if spec.md and design.md use different FR numbering schemes, executor agents get confused — validate numbering consistency before task creation</item>
        <item>Human approval of spec.md is a required checkpoint before design begins — agents must not auto-proceed</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/spec.md" purpose="Complete spec.md template with all required sections and placeholder text"/>
      <template path="templates/spec-trace-check.sh" purpose="Bash script to verify every FR-X references a US and has an AC"/>
    </templates>
